          "body": "Verse 11 is stark: the commanders of the Assyrian king 'captured Manasseh with hooks, bound him with bronze chains, and took him to Babylon.' The hook in the nose was an Assyrian technique used on captured enemies, documented in Assyrian reliefs and inscriptions — including Esarhaddon's own annals, which list 'Menasi, king of Yaudu' among vassal kings who transported building materials to Nineveh. The historical plausibility here is strong. In this brutal context — stripped of his throne, bound in foreign chains, exiled to the capital of the empire — Manasseh 'entreated the Lord his God and humbled himself greatly before the God of his fathers' (v. 12). The verb kana (to humble, subdue, bring low) is the Chronicler's theological keyword for the posture that unlocks restoration throughout 2 Chronicles. Howard Hendricks once observed that the same fire that melts wax hardens clay — affliction either breaks the proud heart or hardens it further. For Manasseh, the chains did what the prophets could not: they produced kana. And God 'was moved by his entreaty and heard his supplication' — the Hebrew atar means to be opened to, to receive the plea. God's response is not grudging or delayed; He hears and acts."
