          "body": "Verse 13 closes the Babylonian episode with the most important sentence in the chapter: 'Then Manasseh knew that the LORD was God.' The verb yada (to know) in this usage is not merely intellectual acknowledgment but experiential recognition — the covenant knowledge that comes from encounter. Manasseh had heard the claims; now he knew the reality. This knowledge produces fruit. Upon return to Jerusalem, the restored king reorganizes Judah's military (v. 14), removes every idol and pagan altar from the temple precincts and the city (v. 15), restores the LORD's altar with peace offerings and thank offerings (v. 16), and commands Judah to serve the LORD God of Israel (v. 16). Douglas Moo's observation about Paul — that genuine encounter with Christ always produces behavioral consequence — applies here in an Old Testament register. The reform is concrete: walls built, idols thrown outside the city, the altar reestablished, Judah instructed. Repentance that changes nothing is not yet repentance. Verse 17 enters a cautionary note — 'nevertheless the people still sacrificed in the high places' — reminding the reader that the corruption Manasseh had seeded over decades could not be fully uprooted in the remaining years of his reign. True repentance does not automatically undo the damage one's leadership has done to others."
